{"event": "tool_call", "tool": "think", "args": {"thought": "\nKey finding from the accessibility snapshot in the Firefox error context:\n\n**TC-83238 — \"Set your store\" link:**\nLooking at the snapshot, I can see:\n- Line 171: `radio \"Product Ship to Store Pickup Fulfillment Type\" [ref=e179]` - present\n- Line 172: `heading \"Free Ship to My Store\" [level=4] [ref=e180]` - it says \"Ship to My Store\", not \"Set your store\"\n- Line 174: `paragraph [ref=e182]: Ready for pickup in 3-5 business days at Granville & Georgia` - a store is ALREADY set!\n- Line 175-176: `paragraph [ref=e183] [cursor=pointer]: Why can't I pick up this today?` and `paragraph [ref=e184] [cursor=pointer]: Check Availability at other stores`\n\nThere's NO \"Set your store\" link! The store was already set (possibly from a previous test run leaving state, or the browser has geolocation/stored state). In Firefox/WebKit, the in-store pickup section already shows a store (Granville & Georgia), so there's no \"Set your store\" link visible.\n\nThe \"Set your store\" link only appears when NO store is set. In Firefox/WebKit, the test is finding a store already selected (possibly from cookies or browser storage from a previous test). \n\n**Root cause for TC-83238:**\nThe store is already set when the test runs in Firefox/WebKit. The \"Set your store\" link never appears because a store is already selected. The fix should be:\n1. Check if the store is already set and if so, skip the store selection step (or clear stored state)\n2. Or use a more robust approach: check if the \"Set your store\" link exists, and if not, if a store is already set\n\nActually wait - looking more carefully. The snapshot shows \"Ship to My Store\" (store already set), with text \"Ready for pickup in 3-5 business days at Granville & Georgia\". So the store IS already set. This happens when the browser has stored state from a previous test.\n\nThe fix for TC-83238: The openStoreSelectorDialog method should handle the case where the store may already be set. We need to:\n- Either use `storageState` to reset cookies/localStorage between tests\n- Or detect if a store is already set and look for a different link (like \"Check Availability at other stores\" or some \"Change Store\" link)\n- Or the simplest fix: make the selector more flexible, or add a check first\n\nActually the real issue is that when a store IS already set, the link shows \"Check Availability at other stores\" or \"Change store\" rather than \"Set your store\". We need to handle both cases.\n\nBut wait - if the store is already set to Granville & Georgia, why would the In-Store Pickup test still fail? The test is trying to SET a store using postal code V6B 1A1. If a store is already set, maybe we need to change the store.\n\nLooking at the test flow:\n1. Navigate to vitamins PDP\n2. Open store selector dialog (fails - \"Set your store\" not visible)\n3. Search stores with V6B 1A1\n4. Select first store\n5. Verify In-Store Pickup is now selected\n\nThe issue is that when a store is already set, the link text changes from \"Set your store\" to something else (probably a \"Change Store\" or \"Check Availability at other stores\" link).\n\n**Fix for TC-83238:** The `setYourStoreLink` selector should also handle when a store is already set. We need to make the openStoreSelectorDialog handle both cases, or find a link that opens the store selector regardless of store state.\n\nActually from the snapshot:\n- `paragraph [ref=e183] [cursor=pointer]: Why can't I pick up this today?`\n- `paragraph [ref=e184] [cursor=pointer]: Check Availability at other stores`\n\nThere's no explicit \"Change Store\" link visible. But there might be one that wasn't captured or the test should look for the store name (Granville & Georgia) to click on it.\n\nOR - maybe the simplest fix: Since In-Store Pickup already has a store set in Firefox/WebKit, the test should also check if In-Store Pickup radio is already visible and clickable, and just click it to select it, then verify cart counter. If the pickup radio is already there, just click Add to Cart.\n\nBut wait - the test's purpose is to test \"In-Store Pickup using postal code V6B 1A1\". If a store is already set from stored state, we might need to clear the state.\n\nThe cleanest fix: in `playwright.config.ts`, add `storageState` reset per test or use `use: { storageState: undefined }`. But this could affect other tests.\n\nAlternatively, we can modify `openStoreSelectorDialog` to:\n1. First check if the \"Set your store\" link is visible\n2. If not, check if the store pickup section is already shown (store already set)\n3. If store is already set, look for another link to open the store selector (like the store name itself, or \"Check Availability at other stores\")\n\nWait - actually the simplest fix: Look at \"Check Availability at other stores\" which is a cursor-pointer paragraph. We can use that to open the store selector. Let me check if clicking that opens the same dialog.\n\nActually the better approach: make the selector more flexible. Update `openStoreSelectorDialog` to try both \"Set your store\" AND if that's not found, click the \"Check Availability at other stores\" link:\n\n```typescript\nasync openStoreSelectorDialog(): Promise<void> {\n    const setStoreLink = this.page.locator('p.cursor-pointer.text-primary').filter({ hasText: /set your store/i }).first();\n    const changeStoreLink = this.page.locator('p.cursor-pointer').filter({ hasText: /check availability at other stores/i }).first();\n    \n    // Wait for either the \"Set your store\" or \"Check Availability\" link\n    await Promise.race([\n        setStoreLink.waitFor({ state: 'visible', timeout: 15_000 }),\n        changeStoreLink.waitFor({ state: 'visible', timeout: 15_000 }),\n    ]);\n    \n    if (await setStoreLink.isVisible()) {\n        await setStoreLink.click();\n    } else {\n        await changeStoreLink.click();\n    }\n    await this.storeSelectorDialog.waitFor({ state: 'visible', timeout: 10_000 });\n}\n```\n\n**TC-83232 — Newsletter email input:**\nThe selector `div.bg-primary input[type=\"email\"]` times out. The issue is that the newsletter section requires scrolling to trigger lazy loading. Let me look at what actually works - the test already does `window.scrollTo(0, document.body.scrollHeight)` but the page's scroll height might be calculated before all content loads.\n\nThe fix: Add multiple scroll attempts or use `page.locator('section').last().scrollIntoViewIfNeeded()` before waiting. Also, the `div.bg-primary` class might have changed. We should try a more flexible selector or scroll more aggressively.\n\nLooking at the test-results, there's no accessibility snapshot for TC-83232 (the chromium folder only has error-context.md). Let me check what's in the snapshot portion of that file.\n\n**TC-83240 — Login:**\nThe login selector `input[name=\"email\"][type=\"email\"]` times out. The issue is navigating to `/myaccount` redirects to login page but the element takes longer to load or the redirect destination is different.\n\nThe fix options:\n1. Navigate directly to `/myaccount/login` instead of `/myaccount`\n2. Increase the timeout\n3. Add a `page.waitForLoadState('networkidle')` before waiting for the element\n\nActually, looking at it more carefully - navigating to `/myaccount` when not logged in should redirect to the login page. But if the redirect is happening (chromium and edge fail, but we need to understand if it's a redirect timing issue). The timeout is 15s which should be enough.\n\nMaybe the UAT site's login page has changed its HTML structure. The input might have a different `name` attribute or the form might be rendered client-side and takes longer.\n\nLet me look at the TC-83240 error context for more clues.\n"}}
