{"event": "tool_call", "tool": "think", "args": {"thought": "\nNow I have a clear picture. Let me also check the geolocation setting: `{ latitude: 49.2827, longitude: -123.1207 }` - this is Vancouver, BC. So the browser has a geolocation set to Vancouver. This means the UAT site might be automatically setting a store based on this geolocation.\n\nFor **TC-83238** (firefox/webkit), the store \"Granville & Georgia\" is already set. This is because:\n1. The geolocation is set to Vancouver (49.2827, -123.1207) \n2. The UAT site picks up this geolocation and auto-sets a nearby store\n3. When a store is already set, the \"Set your store\" link is replaced by \"Check Availability at other stores\" \n\nThe store shows \"Granville & Georgia\" which is a store in downtown Vancouver. This makes sense given the geolocation.\n\n**Key insight**: The geolocation is set in `playwright.config.ts`, so ALL browsers should have the same geolocation. But TC-83238 passes in chromium and edge but fails in firefox and webkit. Why?\n\nThis might be because:\n1. The site detects geolocation differently across browsers\n2. Firefox/WebKit handle the `permissions: ['geolocation']` differently and actually send the geolocation coordinates to the site\n3. Chromium/Edge might not be sending geolocation to the site (maybe the site doesn't request it or it's blocked differently)\n\nOR more likely: the test order matters. If tests run in parallel, a previous test in chromium might have set the store and it's cached in the storageState. But in Firefox/WebKit, the store is already set from a different source.\n\nActually, looking at it more carefully - all browsers have the SAME geolocation configured in config. The difference is:\n- Chromium/Edge: \"Set your store\" link IS visible (no store set) → test PASSES  \n- Firefox/WebKit: store already set (Granville & Georgia) → \"Set your store\" link NOT visible → test FAILS\n\nThis inconsistency suggests the site auto-detects location and sets a store on Firefox/WebKit but not on Chromium/Edge. This could be a browser behavior difference in how geolocation permissions work.\n\n**Fix for TC-83238**: Make `openStoreSelectorDialog` handle both cases:\n- If \"Set your store\" link is visible: click it\n- If the store is already set (link shows \"Check Availability at other stores\" or similar): still open the dialog somehow\n\nLooking at the accessibility snapshot, when a store IS set, I see:\n- `paragraph [ref=e183] [cursor=pointer]: Why can't I pick up this today?`\n- `paragraph [ref=e184] [cursor=pointer]: Check Availability at other stores`\n\nNeither of these seems to open a store selector to CHANGE the store. The \"Change store\" functionality might be accessible by clicking on the store name in the \"Ship to My Store\" section.\n\nActually wait - let me look at the snapshot more carefully. The section says \"Free Ship to My Store\" heading, with \"Ready for pickup in 3-5 business days at Granville & Georgia\". The store name \"Granville & Georgia\" might be clickable/linkable to change the store.\n\nLet me update the `setYourStoreLink` to also match when a store is already set:\n- Option 1: Accept both \"Set your store\" and some \"change\" link\n- Option 2: Make the openStoreSelectorDialog smarter - if the element isn't visible, check if a store is already set and navigate differently\n\nActually the simplest approach: Expand the `setYourStoreLink` to also match \"Check Availability at other stores\" OR any of the other clickable paragraphs that open the store selector.\n\nBut actually the more robust fix: In `openStoreSelectorDialog`, wait for the fulfillment section to load, then check which state we're in:\n1. If \"Set your store\" link exists and is visible → click it\n2. If store is already set → look for a way to change it\n\nLet me think about what \"Change store\" looks like in the DOM. From the snapshot I see the radio button for \"Product Ship to Store Pickup Fulfillment Type\" is present (not checked, Ship to Home is checked). The store name \"Granville & Georgia\" appears as part of the \"Ship to My Store\" option description. \n\nMaybe clicking on the \"Free Ship to My Store\" heading or the store option itself opens the store selector? Or maybe there's a \"Change\" link I'm missing?\n\nActually, looking at the snapshot more carefully:\n- The \"Ship to Store\" radio IS present and the store IS set (Granville & Georgia)\n- But In-Store Pickup radio is NOT checked (Ship to Home is checked)\n- To select In-Store Pickup with the SPECIFIC store V6B 1A1, we need to be able to change the store\n\nFor now, the simplest fix that addresses the actual test failure is:\n- Make the selector fall back to other UI elements when \"Set your store\" isn't found\n- OR: the test should pass if a store is ALREADY set and we just need to select the In-Store Pickup radio and verify it works\n\nActually wait - the test is specifically testing \"using postal code V6B 1A1\". If a store is already set to Granville & Georgia, we need to change it to the one at V6B 1A1. \n\nOR, we could accept the pre-set store and just click In-Store Pickup. The test validates the mini cart counter increments - the specific store doesn't matter for that validation.\n\nBut the test title says \"postal V6B 1A1\" - the test intends to test the postal code entry. However, if in Firefox/WebKit a store is already set, we could:\n1. Click \"Check Availability at other stores\" to try to change it\n2. Or adapt the test to handle both scenarios\n\nThe most pragmatic fix for the `openStoreSelectorDialog` method:\n```typescript\nasync openStoreSelectorDialog(): Promise<void> {\n    const setStoreLink = this.page.locator('p.cursor-pointer.text-primary').filter({ hasText: /set your store/i }).first();\n    const checkAvailabilityLink = this.page.locator('p.cursor-pointer').filter({ hasText: /check availability at other stores/i }).first();\n    \n    // Wait for the PDP fulfillment section to render\n    await this.page.locator('[aria-label=\"Product Ship to Store Pickup Fulfillment Type\"]').waitFor({ state: 'attached', timeout: 15_000 });\n    \n    if (await setStoreLink.isVisible({ timeout: 2_000 })) {\n        await setStoreLink.click();\n    } else if (await checkAvailabilityLink.isVisible({ timeout: 2_000 })) {\n        await checkAvailabilityLink.click();\n    } else {\n        // Last resort - try set store link regardless\n        await setStoreLink.waitFor({ state: 'visible', timeout: 5_000 });\n        await setStoreLink.click();\n    }\n    await this.storeSelectorDialog.waitFor({ state: 'visible', timeout: 10_000 });\n}\n```\n\nBut wait - if a store is ALREADY set and we click \"Check Availability at other stores\", does that open the store-selector dialog? Looking at the link text, it might open a different dialog or page, not the store-selector dialog.\n\nActually, the cleanest fix for TC-83238 is to understand WHY it passes in chromium/edge but not in firefox/webkit. The most likely reason is that the store state is NOT being shared between browsers (each browser has its own cookie/storage jar), but the geolocation permission causes the site to auto-set a store in firefox/webkit but not in chromium/edge.\n\nThe fix should be browser-agnostic. The best approach:\n1. Check if we need to scroll to the fulfillment section first\n2. Then handle both \"Set your store\" and \"already set\" states\n\nOR the even simpler fix: **increase the timeout and add a scroll before waiting**. Looking at the test code, `openStoreSelectorDialog` doesn't scroll to the element first. The \"Set your store\" link might be below the fold and in Firefox/WebKit, the intersection observer renders different content.\n\nLet me look at the test again - it calls `navigateToVitaminsPdp` then immediately calls `openStoreSelectorDialog`. If the \"Set your store\" link is lazy-rendered and in Firefox/WebKit the PDP renders slightly differently, maybe we just need to:\n1. Scroll to the fulfillment section first\n2. Give it a few seconds to render\n\nActually no - the snapshot shows a STORE IS ALREADY SET (\"Granville & Georgia\") in Firefox. The \"Set your store\" link literally doesn't exist because the store is set.\n\n**Most pragmatic fix for TC-83238**: Update `openStoreSelectorDialog` to also try clicking the \"Check Availability at other stores\" link if \"Set your store\" is not visible. This will open the store selector dialog and allow the user to change the store.\n\nNow for **TC-83232 and TC-83240** - the page snapshot shows `img \"Loading...\"`. This means the page is genuinely stuck. The `BasePage.navigate()` only waits for `domcontentloaded` and then `load` (with a 15s timeout, after which it clicks body). But on this UAT site, the React/Next.js app might take longer to hydrate.\n\nKey fixes:\n1. After `navigate`, wait for a visible element (like the header/nav) to confirm hydration\n2. Add more scroll iterations in TC-83232 to trigger lazy loading of newsletter section\n3. For login, ensure we wait longer for the page to render\n\nLet me now look at what specific changes to make:\n\n**Fix 1 — BasePage.navigate()**: After dismissing loading, wait a bit more or wait for a known element.\n\n**Fix 2 — HomePage newsletterEmailInput**: \n- The selector `div.bg-primary input[type=\"email\"]` might need to change\n- OR the scroll strategy needs improvement\n- Looking at test code - it does `window.scrollTo(0, document.body.scrollHeight)` then waits for newsletter input\n- Problem: if the page is showing a loading spinner, the body height is minimal and the footer never renders\n\n**Fix 3 — LoginPage.login()**: \n- The selector `input[name=\"email\"][type=\"email\"]` is standard\n- The issue is the redirect to `/myaccount` shows a loading state\n- Fix: add `page.waitForLoadState('networkidle')` or wait for header to be visible before waiting for email input\n\n**Fix 4 — ProductDetailPage.openStoreSelectorDialog()**: Handle already-set-store case.\n\nLet me now look at what the newsletter section actually looks like. The selector has `div.bg-primary` - but maybe the classes changed. Since I can't load the live site via browser tool, let me work with what I know and make robust fixes.\n\nFor the newsletter test specifically, a better scroll strategy would be:\n1. First wait for the page to be fully loaded (not just dom loaded)  \n2. Then scroll incrementally to trigger lazy rendering\n3. Also try `scrollIntoView` on the footer or last element\n\nFor login - add `page.waitForLoadState('networkidle')` or wait for a header element.\n\nNow let me implement the fixes:\n"}}
